AA Project - Learning about Pet Adoption using PetFinder.my Dataset¶

Dataset¶

The dataset to be analysed is PetFinder_dataset.csv, made avaliable together with this project description. This dataset, downloaded from Kaggle, contains selected and modified data from the following competition: PetFinder.my Adoption Prediction.

PetFinder.my has been Malaysia’s leading animal welfare platform since 2008, with a database of more than 150,000 animals. PetFinder collaborates closely with animal lovers, media, corporations, and global organizations to improve animal welfare. Animal adoption rates are strongly correlated to the metadata associated with their online profiles, such as descriptive text and photo characteristics. As one example, PetFinder is currently experimenting with a simple AI tool called the Cuteness Meter, which ranks how cute a pet is based on qualities present in their photos. In this competition data scientists are supposed to develop machine learning approaches to predict the adoptability of pets - specifically, how quickly is a pet adopted? If successful, they will be adapted into AI tools that will guide shelters and rescuers around the world on improving their pet profiles' appeal, reducing animal suffering and euthanization. In this project, your team is supposed to use only tabular data (not Images or Image Metadata) and see how far you can go in predicting and understanding PetFinder.my adoptions. You should use both supervised and unsupervised learning to tackle 2 tasks:

  1. Task 1 (Supervised Learning) - Predicting Adoption and Adoption Speed
  2. Task 2 (Unsupervised Learning) - Charactering Pets and their Adoption Speed

The PetFinder_dataset.csv your machine learning algorithms should learn from has 14.993 instances described by 24 data fields that you might use as categorical/numerical features and corresponds to a modified version of the train.csv file made available for the competition (https://www.kaggle.com/c/petfinder-adoption-prediction/data). The target in the original Kaggle challenge is Adoption Speed.

File Descriptions¶

  • PetFinder_dataset.csv - Tabular/text data for machine learning.
  • breed_labels.csv - Contains Type and BreedName for each BreedID. Type 1 is dog, 2 is cat.
  • color_labels.csv - Contains ColorName for each ColorID.
  • state_labels.csv - Contains StateName for each StateID.

Data Fields¶

  • PetID - Unique hash ID of pet profile
  • Type - Type of animal (1 = Dog, 2 = Cat)
  • AdoptionSpeed - Categorical speed of adoption. Lower is faster. This is the value to predict in the competition. See section below for more info.
  • Name - Name of pet (Empty if not named)
  • Age - Age of pet when listed, in months
  • Breed1 - Primary breed of pet (see BreedLabels.csv for details)
  • Breed2 - Secondary breed of pet, if pet is of mixed breed (Refer to BreedLabels dictionary)
  • Gender - Gender of pet (1 = Male, 2 = Female, 3 = Mixed, if profile represents group of pets)
  • Color1 - Color 1 of pet (see ColorLabel.csv for details)
  • Color2 - Color 2 of pet (see ColorLabel.csv for details)
  • Color3 - Color 3 of pet (see ColorLabel.csv for details)
  • MaturitySize - Size at maturity (1 = Small, 2 = Medium, 3 = Large, 4 = Extra Large, 0 = Not Specified)
  • FurLength - Fur length (1 = Short, 2 = Medium, 3 = Long, 0 = Not Specified)
  • Vaccinated - Pet has been vaccinated (1 = Yes, 2 = No, 3 = Not Sure)
  • Dewormed - Pet has been dewormed (1 = Yes, 2 = No, 3 = Not Sure)
  • Sterilized - Pet has been spayed / neutered (1 = Yes, 2 = No, 3 = Not Sure)
  • Health - Health Condition (1 = Healthy, 2 = Minor Injury, 3 = Serious Injury, 0 = Not Specified)
  • Quantity - Number of pets represented in profile
  • Fee - Adoption fee (0 = Free)
  • State - State location in Malaysia (Refer to StateLabels dictionary)
  • RescuerID - Unique hash ID of rescuer
  • VideoAmt - Total uploaded videos for this pet
  • PhotoAmt - Total uploaded photos for this pet
  • Description - Profile write-up for this pet. The primary language used is English, with some in Malay or Chinese.

AdoptionSpeed¶

The value of AdoptionSpeed describes how quickly, if at all, a pet is adopted:

  • 0 - Pet was adopted on the same day as it was listed.
  • 1 - Pet was adopted between 1 and 7 days (1st week) after being listed.
  • 2 - Pet was adopted between 8 and 30 days (1st month) after being listed.
  • 3 - Pet was adopted between 31 and 90 days (2nd & 3rd month) after being listed.
  • 4 - No adoption after 100 days of being listed. (There are no pets in this dataset that waited between 90 and 100 days).

Important Notes on Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

  1. Data can contain errors/typos, whose correction might improve the analysis.
  2. Some features can contain many values, whose grouping in categories (aggregation into bins) might improve the analysis.
  3. Data can contain missing values, that you might decide to fill. You might also decide to eliminate instances/features with high percentages of missing values.
  4. Not all features are necessarily important for the analysis.
  5. Depending on the analysis, some features might have to be excluded.
  6. Class distribution is an important characteristic of the dataset that should be carefully taken into consideration. Class imbalance might impair machine learning.

  • Data Cleaning and Preprocessing in Orange: https://docs.biolab.si//3/visual-programming/widgets/data/preprocess.html

df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Replace numeric values with descriptive labels
label_dict = {
    'Gender': {1: 'Male', 2: 'Female', 3: 'Mixed'},
    'Vaccinated': {1: 'Yes', 2: 'No', 3: 'Not Sure'},
    'Dewormed': {1: 'Yes', 2: 'No', 3: 'Not Sure'},
    'Sterilized': {1: 'Yes', 2: 'No', 3: 'Not Sure'},
    'Health': {0: 'Not Specified', 1: 'Healthy', 2: 'Minor Injury', 3: 'Serious Injury'},
    'MaturitySize': {0: 'Not Specified', 1: 'Small', 2: 'Medium', 3: 'Large', 4: 'Extra Large'},
    'FurLength': {0: 'Not Specified', 1: 'Short', 2: 'Medium', 3: 'Long'},
    'AdoptionSpeed': {0: 'Same Day', 1: '1-7 Days', 2: '1-30 Days', 3: '31-90 Days', 4: 'Not Adopted'}
}

for column, mapping in label_dict.items():

# List of columns to plot

# Loop through the columns and create bar plots or histograms
for i, col in enumerate(columns_to_plot, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 3, i)  # Create a grid of 4 rows and 3 columns for the plots
    if df[col].dtype == 'object' or df[col].dtype == 'category':  # Categorical columns
        ax = df[col].value_counts().sort_index().plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
        plt.title(f'{col} Distribution')
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')

        # Rotate x labels to 45 degrees where necessary (e.g., long category names)
        if len(df[col].value_counts()) > 5:  # Check if there are many unique values
            plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    else:  # For numerical columns like 'Age' and 'Quantity', we'll use histograms
        if col == 'Age':
            # Bin 'Age' into categories for better visualization
            age_bins = [0, 1, 3, 6, 12, 18, 24, 30]
            df['Age_binned'] = pd.cut(df['Age'], bins=age_bins, right=False)

            df[col].plot(kind='hist', bins=30, color='lightgreen', edgecolor='black')
            plt.title(f'{col} Distribution')
            plt.xlabel(col)
            plt.ylabel('Frequency')

    # Adjust layout to prevent overlap
    plt.tight_layout()

1.1. Specific Data Preprocessing for Classification¶

Binary Classification: Predicting Adoption¶

  1. Preprocessing:
    The dataset is preprocessed by removing irrelevant columns, converting the target variable (AdoptionSpeed) to a binary label (Adopted), and encoding categorical features using Label Encoding for ordinal columns and One-Hot Encoding for nominal columns.

  2. Model Training:
    Five different classifiers are trained using 5-fold cross-validation to predict whether a pet will be adopted (binary classification). The classifiers used include Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and SVM.

  3. Evaluation:
    After training, each classifier is evaluated on the test set using accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and confusion matrix. The confusion matrix is visualized using a heatmap to better understand the model’s predictions.

In [3]:
df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Define a function to preprocess data for binary classification
def preprocess_binary_classification(df):
    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # Convert 'AdoptionSpeed' to binary 'Adopted' column: 1 if AdoptionSpeed != 4, 0 if AdoptionSpeed == 4
    df_cleaned['Adopted'] = df_cleaned['AdoptionSpeed'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x != 4 else 0)
    
    # Drop the original 'AdoptionSpeed' as it's no longer needed for binary classification
    df_cleaned = df_cleaned.drop(columns=['AdoptionSpeed'])
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Preprocess the data for binary classification
data_cleaned = preprocess_binary_classification(df)

# Prepare features (X) and target (y)
X_binary = data_cleaned.drop(columns=['Adopted'])
y_binary = data_cleaned['Adopted']

# Train-Test Split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_binary, y_binary, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Initialize classifiers
classifiers = {
    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(),
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(),
    'Naive Bayes': GaussianNB(),
    'SVM': SVC()
}

# Store cross-validation results for each classifier
cv_results = {}

# Train each classifier using cross-validation and store the results
for name, clf in classifiers.items():
    print(f"\nTraining {name}...")
    
    # Perform cross-validation (5-fold)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_results[name] = cv_scores
    
    # Output the results of cross-validation
    print(f"{name} Accuracy: Mean = {np.mean(cv_scores):.4f}, Std Dev = {np.std(cv_scores):.4f}")

# Evaluate classifiers on the test set using classification report and confusion matrix
for name, clf in classifiers.items():
    print(f"\nEvaluating {name} on the test set...")
    
    # Fit the model on the training data
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Predict on the test data
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    
    # Classification report (precision, recall, f1-score)
    print(f"Classification Report for {name}:\n{classification_report(y_test, y_pred)}")
    
    # Confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f"Confusion Matrix for {name}:\n{cm}")
    
    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', xticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'], yticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {name}')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()

Enhanced Binary Classification with Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  1. Data Preprocessing:
    The dataset is preprocessed by filling missing values, dropping irrelevant columns, and transforming the target variable AdoptionSpeed into a binary target Adopted (1 for adopted pets, 0 for non-adopted). Categorical columns are encoded using Label Encoding for ordinal features and One-Hot Encoding for nominal features.

  2. Model Training & Evaluation:
    Five classifiers are trained (Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and SVM) and evaluated on a binary classification task. Cross-validation scores and confusion matrices are displayed for each classifier, and classification performance is assessed using precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC AUC.

  3. ROC AUC & Precision-Recall Curve:
    For classifiers capable of providing probability estimates (SVM, Random Forest, and Logistic Regression), ROC AUC and Precision-Recall AUC scores are computed to evaluate model performance on imbalanced classes.

  4. Hyperparameter Tuning (Random Forest):
    GridSearchCV is used for hyperparameter tuning on the Random Forest classifier to find the optimal parameters, followed by re-evaluation on the test set with the best model.

df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Define a function to preprocess data for binary classification
def preprocess_binary_classification(df):
    # Handle missing values (fill with mode for categorical, mean for numerical)
    df = df.fillna(df.mode().iloc[0])  # Fill categorical columns with mode
    
    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # Convert 'AdoptionSpeed' to binary 'Adopted' column: 1 if AdoptionSpeed != 4, 0 if AdoptionSpeed == 4
    df_cleaned['Adopted'] = df_cleaned['AdoptionSpeed'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x != 4 else 0)
    
    # Drop the original 'AdoptionSpeed' as it's no longer needed for binary classification
    df_cleaned = df_cleaned.drop(columns=['AdoptionSpeed'])
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Preprocess the data for binary classification

    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', annot_kws={"size": 14}, 
                xticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'], yticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'])
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {name}')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.show()

    # ROC AUC Score (for SVM, Random Forest, Logistic Regression)
    if name in ['SVM', 'Random Forest', 'Logistic Regression']:
        y_pred_prob = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Probability estimates for the positive class
        auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_prob)
        print(f"ROC AUC for {name}: {auc_score:.4f}")
        
        # Precision-Recall Curve and AUC
        precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
        pr_auc = auc(recall, precision)
        print(f"Precision-Recall AUC for {name}: {pr_auc:.4f}")
    
    # Hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV (for Random Forest as an example)
    if name == 'Random Forest':
        param_grid = {
            'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
            'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30],
            'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
            'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4]
        }
        grid_search = GridSearchCV(clf, param_grid, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, scoring='accuracy')
        grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
        print(f"Best parameters for {name}: {grid_search.best_params_}")
        print(f"Best cross-validation score for {name}: {grid_search.best_score_:.4f}")
        
        # Re-evaluate with the best parameters found by GridSearchCV
        best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_
        y_pred_rf = best_rf.predict(X_test)
        print(f"Classification Report for Random Forest (tuned):\n{classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf)}")
        
        # Confusion Matrix for the tuned model
        cm_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf)
        print(f"Confusion Matrix for Random Forest (tuned):\n{cm_rf}")
        
        # Plot confusion matrix
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
        sns.heatmap(cm_rf, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', annot_kws={"size": 14}, 
                    xticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'], yticklabels=['Not Adopted', 'Adopted'])
        plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - Random Forest (Tuned)')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted')
        plt.ylabel('Actual')
        plt.show()

1.2. Learning and Evaluating Classifiers¶

Multiclass Classification with Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  1. Data Preprocessing:
    The dataset is preprocessed by filling missing values, dropping irrelevant columns, and encoding both ordinal and nominal categorical features. The target variable AdoptionSpeed remains unchanged (with 5 classes: 0 to 4).

  2. Model Training & Evaluation:
    Five classifiers (Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and SVM) are trained on the dataset, evaluated using cross-validation, and assessed on the test set. The performance is measured with a classification report (precision, recall, F1-score) and confusion matrix.

  3. Confusion Matrix Visualization:
    The confusion matrix for each model is plotted to visualize the classification performance across the 5 possible target classes (0-4).

  4. Hyperparameter Tuning (Random Forest):
    For Random Forest, hyperparameter tuning is performed using GridSearchCV to find the optimal model parameters. The best model is then re-evaluated on the test set, and its confusion matrix is plotted to compare performance before and after tuning.

df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Define a function to preprocess data for multiclass classification
def preprocess_multiclass_classification(df):
    # Handle missing values (fill with mode for categorical, mean for numerical)
    df = df.fillna(df.mode().iloc[0])  # Fill categorical columns with mode
    
    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # The target variable is AdoptionSpeed (original 5 classes: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4)
    # No transformation needed for the target here; we will keep it as it is.
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Preprocess the data for multiclass classification
data_cleaned = preprocess_multiclass_classification(df)

# Prepare features (X) and target (y)
X_multiclass = data_cleaned.drop(columns=['AdoptionSpeed'])

    'Decision Tree': DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(),
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    'Naive Bayes': GaussianNB(),
    'SVM': SVC(probability=True)  # Ensure SVM outputs probabilities for metrics like ROC AUC
}

# Store cross-validation results for each classifier
cv_results = {}

# Train each classifier using cross-validation and store the results
for name, clf in classifiers.items():
    print(f"\nTraining {name}...")
    
    # Perform cross-validation (5-fold)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_results[name] = cv_scores
    
    # Output the results of cross-validation
    print(f"{name} Accuracy: Mean = {np.mean(cv_scores):.4f}, Std Dev = {np.std(cv_scores):.4f}")

# Evaluate classifiers on the test set using classification report and confusion matrix
for name, clf in classifiers.items():
    print(f"\nEvaluating {name} on the test set...")
    
    # Fit the model on the training data
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Predict on the test data
    y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    
    # Classification report (precision, recall, f1-score) for multiclass
    print(f"Classification Report for {name}:\n{classification_report(y_test, y_pred)}")
    
    # Confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f"Confusion Matrix for {name}:\n{cm}")

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', annot_kws={"size": 14},

1.3. Classification - Final Discussion and Conclusions¶

This section classifies pet adoption data from the PetFinder dataset into two categories:

  1. Binary Classification (Adopted vs Not Adopted):

    • The target variable is derived from the 'AdoptionSpeed' column, where pets with an adoption speed of 4 (not adopted) are labeled as 0, and all others as 1 (adopted).
    • The script handles data preprocessing by encoding categorical features (like type, color, health, etc.) using label encoding and one-hot encoding.
    • Various classifiers (Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, and SVM) are trained and evaluated for binary classification.

  2. Multiclass Classification (Adoption Speed: 0-4):

    • This classification predicts the adoption speed (0: very fast, 4: very slow) of pets based on features such as pet type, age, and health status.
    • Data preprocessing includes encoding ordinal categorical variables and one-hot encoding for nominal variables.
    • The classifiers are also trained and evaluated for multiclass classification.

The code performs the following steps:

  • Data Preprocessing: Cleans the dataset by handling missing values, encoding categorical features, and splitting the data into train and test sets.
  • Model Training: Uses a variety of classifiers to fit the models for both binary and multiclass problems.
  • Model Evaluation: Evaluates model performance using classification reports and confusion matrices, visualized through heatmaps.

The dataset is split into separate sets for cats and dogs, allowing for both binary and multiclass classification tasks to be performed on each group separately.

df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Preprocess the data for binary classification (Adopted)
def preprocess_binary_classification(df):
    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # Convert 'AdoptionSpeed' to binary 'Adopted' column: 1 if AdoptionSpeed != 4, 0 if AdoptionSpeed == 4
    df_cleaned['Adopted'] = df_cleaned['AdoptionSpeed'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x != 4 else 0)
    
    # Drop the original 'AdoptionSpeed' as it's no longer needed for binary classification
    df_cleaned = df_cleaned.drop(columns=['AdoptionSpeed'])
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Function to preprocess for multiclass classification (AdoptionSpeed)

    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # Convert 'AdoptionSpeed' to a multiclass target
    df_cleaned['AdoptionSpeed'] = df_cleaned['AdoptionSpeed'].astype(int)
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)

Task 2 (Unsupervised Learning) - Charactering Pets and their Adoption Speed¶

In this task you should use unsupervised learning to characterize pets and their adoption speed. You have 2 clustering:

  1. Use Clustering algorithms to find similar groups of adopted pets. When animals are adopted, is it possible to find groups of pets with the same/similar adoption speed? Evaluate clustering results using internal and external metrics.
  2. Be creative and define and explore your own unsupervised learning task! What else would it be interesting to find out?

2.1. Preprocessing Data for Clustering¶

This section of the script applies unsupervised learning techniques to cluster the pets based on their features and explore patterns in the adoption process using the PetFinder dataset. The main focus is to uncover relationships between pet characteristics and their adoption speed without using explicit labels.

  1. Data Preprocessing for Clustering:

    • Irrelevant columns for clustering (e.g., PetID, RescuerID, etc.) are removed.
    • Categorical features (such as pet type, color, health, etc.) are transformed using Label Encoding (for ordinal categories) and One-Hot Encoding (for nominal categories).
    • The data is standardized using StandardScaler to normalize the features, which is important for clustering algorithms like KMeans.

  2. KMeans Clustering:

    • The data is clustered using the KMeans algorithm into 5 clusters, based on the assumption of 5 different adoption speeds (ranging from 0 to 4).
    • The clustering model is trained on the data of adopted pets (excluding those not adopted), and each pet is assigned to one of the clusters.

  3. Evaluation:

    • Silhouette Score: Measures how similar each pet is to its own cluster compared to other clusters (higher scores indicate better clustering).
    • Adjusted Rand Index (ARI): Compares the clustering results to the actual adoption speeds, providing an external validation of the clustering performance.

  4. Visualization:

    • PCA (Principal Component Analysis) is used to reduce the dimensionality of the data to 2 components for easy visualization.
    • The clustering results and true adoption speeds are visualized in a 2D scatter plot, allowing a comparison of how well the clusters correspond to actual adoption speed categories.

The overall goal is to see if the unsupervised KMeans algorithm can reveal meaningful patterns in the adoption process, potentially linking certain pet characteristics to their likelihood of adoption speed.

In [7]:
df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Define preprocessing function for clustering
def preprocess_for_clustering(df):
    # Drop irrelevant columns for clustering
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])  # Remove only columns relevant to clustering
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Apply Label Encoding to ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])
    
    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    # Standardize the features (important for clustering)
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    df_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df_cleaned)
    
    return df_scaled

# Preprocess the data
X_scaled = preprocess_for_clustering(df)

# Task 2.1: Clustering with KMeans
# We will try to find groups based on the `AdoptionSpeed` column to see if clustering algorithms can uncover patterns related to adoption speed.

# 1. First, we separate pets based on their adoption speed (5 classes: {0, 1, 2, 3, 4})
df_adopted = df[df['AdoptionSpeed'] != 4]  # We will focus on adopted pets (AdoptionSpeed != 4)
X_adopted_scaled = preprocess_for_clustering(df_adopted)

# 2. Apply KMeans Clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=42)
df_adopted['Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_adopted_scaled)

# 3. Evaluate the Clustering Performance
# Internal Metric: Silhouette Score
sil_score = silhouette_score(X_adopted_scaled, df_adopted['Cluster'])
print(f"Silhouette Score for KMeans: {sil_score:.4f}")

# External Metric: Adjusted Rand Index (ARI)
# We compare the clustering results with the true labels (AdoptionSpeed)
ari_score = adjusted_rand_score(df_adopted['AdoptionSpeed'], df_adopted['Cluster'])
print(f"Adjusted Rand Index for KMeans: {ari_score:.4f}")

# 4. Visualize the Clustering Results
# We will reduce the dimensionality of the data using PCA (Principal Component Analysis) for visualization

pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_adopted_scaled)

2.2. Learning and Evaluating Clusterings¶

In this section, unsupervised learning is applied to the PetFinder dataset using KMeans clustering. The objective is to identify distinct groups of pets based on their characteristics, without using any labeled data (i.e., no adoption speed or outcome is used during clustering).

  1. Data Preprocessing:

    • Irrelevant columns (such as PetID, RescuerID, etc.) are removed to focus on the features related to pet characteristics.
    • Categorical variables are processed using Label Encoding for ordinal variables (e.g., MaturitySize, FurLength) and One-Hot Encoding for nominal variables (e.g., Gender, Color1, State).
    • The dataset is then standardized using StandardScaler to normalize the feature values, which is essential for clustering.

  2. Feature Selection:

    • A subset of relevant features, such as Age, Health, Fee, and Quantity, is selected for clustering, as these are expected to influence the pet's characteristics and potential adoption speed.

  3. KMeans Clustering:

    • KMeans is used to cluster the pets into 4 groups. The number of clusters (n_clusters=4) is chosen based on an assumption of potential groupings within the data, but this could be adjusted based on further analysis.
    • The cluster labels are then added to the data, allowing each pet to be assigned to one of the 4 clusters.

  4. Evaluation:

    • The clustering performance is assessed using the Silhouette Score, which measures how similar each pet is to its own cluster compared to other clusters. A higher score indicates better-defined clusters.

  5. Visualization:

    • PCA (Principal Component Analysis) is used to reduce the dimensionality of the data to 2 components for easy visualization in a 2D space.
    • A scatter plot is created to visualize how the pets are grouped into clusters based on their characteristics.

  6. Cluster Analysis:

    • The mean values of the selected features are computed for each cluster to explore the characteristics that define each group (e.g., one cluster might have pets with higher health, while another cluster might have younger pets).

The goal of this clustering approach is to uncover hidden patterns in the pet characteristics, which might suggest natural groupings related to pet types, health, age, and adoption potential.

df = pd.read_csv('PetFinder_dataset.csv')


# Preprocess the data (similar to previous steps)
def preprocess_data_for_clustering(df):
    # Drop irrelevant columns
    df_cleaned = df.drop(columns=['PetID', 'RescuerID', 'Name', 'Description'])
    
    # Convert categorical columns to category type
    categorical_columns = ['Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'MaturitySize', 
                           'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health', 'State']
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].astype('category')
    
    # Label encode the ordinal categorical columns
    label_columns = ['MaturitySize', 'FurLength', 'Vaccinated', 'Dewormed', 'Sterilized', 'Health']
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
    for col in label_columns:
        df_cleaned[col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df_cleaned[col])

    # One-Hot Encoding for nominal categorical columns (e.g., 'Type', 'Gender', 'Color1', etc.)
    df_cleaned = pd.get_dummies(df_cleaned, columns=['Gender', 'Color1', 'Color2', 'Color3', 'State', 'Type'], drop_first=True)
    
    return df_cleaned

# Preprocess the data
data_cleaned = preprocess_data_for_clustering(df)

# Select the relevant features for clustering

kmeans.fit(X_scaled)

plt.xlabel('PCA Component 1')

2.3. Clustering - Final Discussion and Conclusions¶

Brief Description for Clustering and Cluster Characterization¶

This section applies KMeans clustering to group pets based on selected numerical features like age, health, sterilization, and adoption fee.

  • Clustering: Pets are clustered into 5 groups using KMeans.
  • Cluster Labels: Each pet is assigned a cluster label.
  • Cluster Characterization: The average values of features for each cluster are computed to understand group characteristics.
  • Visualization: A heatmap is used to visualize the feature averages for each cluster.

This helps identify patterns in the dataset, such as clusters of pets with similar attributes.

In [9]:
# For the sake of simplicity, let's assume you want to cluster on the numerical features only

3. Final Comments and Conclusions¶

In this project, we performed both supervised and unsupervised learning to analyze the PetFinder dataset. Here's a summary of the findings:

  1. Binary and Multiclass Classification:

    • We trained multiple classification models (e.g., Decision Tree, Random Forest, Logistic Regression, SVM, Naive Bayes) to predict adoption outcomes for pets.
    • For binary classification (adopted vs. not adopted), we observed how different models performed, focusing on precision, recall, and accuracy.
    • For multiclass classification (predicting adoption speed), the models were evaluated for their ability to categorize pets into adoption speed classes, with confusion matrices and classification reports aiding performance evaluation.

  2. Clustering:

    • Using KMeans clustering, we grouped pets based on features like age, health, and adoption fee.
    • We identified 5 clusters that helped characterize pets with similar attributes, which could assist in targeting adoption strategies or understanding common traits in adopted vs. non-adopted pets.

  3. Insights:

    • The clustering results gave valuable insights into the types of pets that could be grouped together, based on their attributes. For example, pets with higher adoption fees and specific health conditions formed distinct groups.
    • The classification models provided a way to predict adoption likelihood, offering useful information for future adoption efforts.

  4. Future Work:

    • Incorporating additional data (e.g., pet photos, owner details) might improve predictive accuracy.
    • More advanced techniques like ensemble methods or deep learning could also be explored to enhance model performance.
    • Clustering could be further refined by experimenting with different numbers of clusters or exploring hierarchical clustering techniques.

In conclusion, this analysis offers a comprehensive approach to understanding pet adoption patterns, with both predictive and exploratory insights.
